The code is mostly following the SOLID principles, but there are a few areas where it could be improved:

**ISP (Interface Segregation Principle)**
```kotlin
interface Device {
    fun getDeviceName(): String 
    fun displayInfo()
}

interface NetworkDevice : Device {
    fun connect()
    fun transferData(data: String)
    fun runDiagnostics()
    fun updateFirmware(version: String)
}

interface MultimediaDevice : Device {
    fun powerOn()
    fun play()
    fun stop()
    fun setVolume(level: Int)
    fun setScreenResolution(resolution: String)
}
```
The `NetworkDevice` and `MultimediaDevice` interfaces are too large, they could be split into smaller more specific interfaces. This would adhere to the ISP as each client (the DeviceManager class in this case) will only have access to methods relevant to its functionality.

**DIP (Dependency Inversion Principle)**
```kotlin
class Router(private val name: String, private val ipAddress: String) : NetworkDevice {...}

class NetworkSwitch(private val name: String, private val ipAddress: String) : NetworkDevice {...}

class SmartTV(private val name: String, private val location: String) : MultimediaDevice {...}

class SmartSpeaker(private val name: String, private val location: String) : MultimediaDevice {...}
```
The classes `Router` and `NetworkSwitch` implement the interface `NetworkDevice`. Similarly, `SmartTV` and `SmartSpeaker` implement the interface `MultimediaDevice`. This is a violation of DIP as the higher level modules (the DeviceManager class) should not depend on the lower level modules directly but instead they should depend on abstractions.

**OCP (Open Closed Principle)**
```kotlin
class DeviceManager {
    fun configureDevice(device: Device) {...}

    fun updateFirmware(device: NetworkDevice) {...}

    fun playMedia(device: MultimediaDevice) {...}

    fun adjustVolume(device: MultimediaDevice, level: Int) {...}
}
```
The `configureDevice` function is open for extension but closed for modification. If a new type of device was added (e.g., a printer), it could be easily integrated into the system without modifying existing code. This follows OCP.

**LSP (Liskov Substitution Principle)**
The classes `Router` and `NetworkSwitch` are not implementing any specific behavior for NetworkDevice, so they can't possibly violate LSP. 

Similarly, the classes `SmartTV` and `SmartSpeaker` are not implementing any specific behavior for MultimediaDevice, so they can't possibly violate LSP either.

**SRP (Single Responsibility Principle)**
Each class has a single responsibility: Router, NetworkSwitch, SmartTV, SmartSpeaker and DeviceManager. 

In conclusion, the code is mostly following SOLID principles but there are some areas where it could be improved to follow these principles more strictly.

