The original code was tightly coupled with the specific implementations of `FlightService`, which made it difficult to test and maintain. The refactored code separates these concerns into two interfaces (`CustomerFlightService` and `AdminFlightService`) that depend on a common interface (`FlightService`). This way, we can easily swap out the implementation of `FlightService` without affecting other parts of our application.

The `searchAvailableFlights()` method in both implementations uses the same repository call to fetch available flights based on origin, destination and departure time. The `updateFlightStatus()` method updates a flight's status by fetching it from the database first (or throwing an exception if not found), then updating its status and saving it back to the database.

The `CustomerFlightService` and `AdminFlightService` classes are now independent of each other, making them easier to test and maintain. They can be used in different parts of our application without affecting each other. 

