**God Object (SRP)**
```csharp
public class EmailService 
{
    public void SendEmail(string recipient, string subject, string body)
    {
        // Code here...
    }

    public void SendSMS(string phoneNumber, string message)
    {
        throw new NotSupportedException("EmailService does not support SMS");
    }
}
```
The `EmailService` class is a God Object as it has more than one responsibility. It's responsible for sending emails and SMS messages. This violates the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) because it has multiple responsibilities. The code should be refactored to separate these functionalities into different classes or interfaces.

**Interface Bloat (ISP)**
```csharp
public interface NotificationSender
{
    void SendEmail(string recipient, string subject, string body);
    void SendSMS(string phoneNumber, string message);
    void SendPushNotification(string deviceId, string title, string message);
    void SendSlackMessage(string channel, string message);
}
```
The `NotificationSender` interface is bloated with methods that are not applicable to all implementations. This violates the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) because it forces clients of this interface to depend on methods they do not use. The code should be refactored to separate these functionalities into different interfaces.

**Inappropriate Intimacy (DIP)**
```csharp
public class EmailService 
{
    public void SendEmail(string recipient, string subject, string body)
    {
        // Code here...
    }
}

public class SMSService 
{
    public void SendSMS(string phoneNumber, string message)
    {
        // Code here...
    }
}
```
The `EmailService` and `SMSService` classes are tightly coupled with each other. This violates the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) because high-level modules should not depend on low-level modules, both should depend on abstractions. The code should be refactored to use dependency injection or a service locator pattern to decouple these classes.

**Overall Rating: 2/5**

The above violations have been rated based on the SOLID principles they violate, with 0 being no violation and 5 being all violations present. The overall rating is calculated as the sum of the ratings for each violation divided by the total number of violations. In this case, there are three violations (SRP, ISP, DIP), so the overall rating would be `(2+1+3)/3 = 2`.

